    "# Executive Summary"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Based on the analysis, we recommend that Intuit leverage the logit model (Logit LR3) with all available features in addition to engineered features to target 190,005 customers out of the available 763,334 customers for wave 2. This approach is expected to yield an expected profit of $561,062 and a Return on Marketing Expense (ROME) of 209%.\n",
    "\n",
    "High-level summary characteristics of Logit LR 3 - best model:\n",
    "- Expected Response Rate: 7%\n",
    "- Breakeven: 2.35%\n",
    "- Expected Revenue: $828,969\n",
    "- Cost: $267,907\n",
    "- Expected ROME: 209%\n",
    "- Expected Profit: $561,062\n",
    "\n",
    "By adopting this strategy, Intuit can significantly enhance its marketing efficiency, achieving a substantial return on its marketing investments and maximizing profitability through an optimized targeting approach."

To avoid merge conflicts, **always** \"pull\" changes to the repo before you start working on any files. Then, when you are done, save and commit your changes, and then push them to GitHub. Make \"pull first\" a habit!\n",

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/markdown": [
       "## Intuit: Quickbooks upgrade\n",
       "\n",
       "The purpose of this exercise is to gain experience modeling the response to an upsell campaign. The `intuit75k.parquet` file contains data on 75,000 (small) businesses that were selected randomly from the 801,821 that were sent the wave-1 mailing. The mailing contained an offer to upgrade to the latest version of the Quickbooks software.\n",
       "\n",
       "Variable `res1` denotes which of these businesses responded to the mailing by purchasing Quickbooks version 3.0 from Intuit Direct. Note that Intuit Direct sells products directly to its customers rather than through a retailer. Use the available data to predict which businesses that did not respond to the wave-1 mailing, are most likely to respond to the wave-2 mailing. Note that variables were added, deleted, and recoded so please ignore the variable descriptions in Exhibit 3 in the case in the course reader. Instead, use the variable descriptions below:\n",
       "\n",
       "## Variable description\n",
       "\n",
       "* id: Small business customer ID\n",
       "* zip5: 5-Digit ZIP Code (00000=unknown, 99999=international ZIPs).\n",
       "* zip_bins: Zip-code bins (20 approx. equal sized bins from lowest to highest zip code number)\n",
       "* sex: Gender Identity \"Female\", \"Male\", or \"Unknown\"\n",
       "* bizflag: Business Flag.  Address contains a Business name (1 = yes, 0 = no or unknown).\n",
       "* numords: Number of orders from Intuit Direct in the previous 36 months\n",
       "* dollars: Total $ ordered from Intuit Direct in the previous 36 months\n",
       "* last: Time (in months) since last order from Intuit Direct in previous 36 months\n",
       "* sincepurch: Time (in months) since original (not upgrade) purchase of Quickbooks\n",
       "* version1: Is 1 if customer's current Quickbooks is version 1, 0 if version 2\n",
       "* owntaxprod: Is 1 if customer purchased tax software, 0 otherwise\n",
       "* upgraded: Is 1 if customer upgraded from Quickbooks vs. 1 to vs. 2\n",
       "* res1: Response to wave 1 mailing (\"Yes\" if responded else \"No\")\n",
       "* training: 70/30 split, 1 for training sample, 0 for validation sample\n"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "intuit_desc = rsm.md(\"data/intuit75k_description.md\")"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Statistical Summary of the Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Numerical Variables Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Count**: All numerical variables have 75,000 non-null entries, confirming the absence of missing values.\n",
    "- **Mean and Standard Deviation**:\n",
    "  - Variables such as `numords`, `dollars`, `last`, and `sincepurch` show a wide range of means and standard deviations, indicating diverse spending patterns and engagement levels with Intuit products.\n",
    "  - `version1`, `owntaxprod`, and `upgraded` are binary indicators with means significantly less than 0.5, suggesting a lower prevalence of these characteristics among the businesses.\n",
    "- **Min and Max**:\n",
    "  - The minimum and maximum values for variables like `dollars` and `last` indicate the range of transaction sizes and recency of engagement.\n",
    "- **Quartiles**:\n",
    "  - The quartile distribution provides insights into the spread of the data, highlighting, for example, that at least 25% of businesses have not ordered in the last 8 months (`last`) and at least 50% have spent $71 or less in the past 36 months (`dollars`).\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Categorical Variables Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Sex**: There are 3 unique values (Male, Female, Unknown), with \"Male\" being the most frequent category.\n",
    "- **Res1**: There are 2 unique responses (Yes, No), with \"No\" overwhelmingly more frequent, indicating a low response rate to the wave 1 mailing.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Insights and Observations\n",
    "\n",
    "- The dataset represents a comprehensive view of customer engagement and response to marketing efforts by Intuit, with a significant variance in customer spending and engagement.\n",
    "- The low mean of `res1_yes` (0.048) reflects the challenge in converting mailings into sales, underscoring the importance of identifying characteristics that predict a higher likelihood of response.\n",
    "- The distribution of categorical variables such as `sex` and `res1` provides a foundational understanding of the demographics and behaviors within the dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1000 with 5 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Setting the aesthetic style of the plots\n",
    "sns.set_style(\"whitegrid\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Creating a figure for subplots\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Histogram for 'dollars'\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)\n",
    "sns.histplot(intuit['dollars'], kde=True, bins=30)\n",
    "plt.title('Distribution of Total Dollars Ordered')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Histogram for 'numords'\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 3, 2)\n",
    "sns.histplot(intuit['numords'], kde=False, bins=5)\n",
    "plt.title('Distribution of Number of Orders')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Histogram for 'last'\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 3, 3)\n",
    "sns.histplot(intuit['last'], kde=True, bins=30)\n",
    "plt.title('Distribution of Time Since Last Order')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Bar chart for 'sex'\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)\n",
    "sns.countplot(x='sex', data=intuit)\n",
    "plt.title('Distribution of Gender Identity')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Bar chart for 'res1'\n",
    "plt.subplot(2, 3, 5)\n",
    "sns.countplot(x='res1', data=intuit)\n",
    "plt.title('Response to Wave 1 Mailing')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Adjust layout\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show plots\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### General Data Visualization Insights\n",
    "\n",
    "The histograms and bar charts provide valuable insights into the dataset's characteristics:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Total Dollars Ordered (`dollars`)**: The distribution shows a right-skewed pattern, indicating that a large number of businesses have spent relatively small amounts with a few outliers spending significantly more. This suggests that most businesses make smaller transactions with Intuit.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Number of Orders (`numords`)**: The distribution is discrete, as expected, with the majority of businesses placing between 1 to 3 orders in the past 36 months. This indicates varied engagement levels among businesses, with a tendency towards lower frequency of orders.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Time Since Last Order (`last`)**: The distribution is fairly uniform, indicating that the dataset includes a wide range of recency from recent to less recent purchasers. It suggests no significant bias towards newly engaged or long-disengaged customers.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Gender Identity (`sex`)**: The majority of the dataset is represented by \"Male\", followed by \"Female\", and a notable portion is categorized as \"Unknown\". This indicates a diversity in the gender identity of the business owners or primary contacts.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Response to Wave 1 Mailing (`res1`)**: The overwhelming majority did not respond to the wave 1 mailing, highlighting the challenge of converting mailings into positive responses. This low response rate underscores the importance of identifying predictive factors for a more targeted approach in wave 2."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "# Adjusting the dataset to create three distinct groups based on ZIP code\n",
    "zip_codes_all = intuit['zip5'].astype(str)  # Ensure zip5 is string for all data\n",
    "zip_codes_grouped_all = zip_codes_all.apply(lambda x: '00801' if x == '00801' else ('00804' if x == '00804' else 'Others'))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Creating a pivot table for the entire dataset with these three groups, with normalization\n",
    "pivot_table_normalized = pd.crosstab(index=zip_codes_grouped_all, columns=intuit['res1_yes'], normalize='index')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Creating a pivot table for the entire dataset with these three groups, without normalization\n",
    "pivot_table_counts = pd.crosstab(index=zip_codes_grouped_all, columns=intuit['res1_yes'])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting the normalized stacked bar chart for the entire dataset\n",
    "ax = pivot_table_normalized.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), color=['#606060', '#D3D3D3'])\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Preparing the data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before proceeding to the analysis, we will change the data types of the categorical variables to category and then split the data into training and testing sets.\n",
    "\n",
    "In addition, we will also create a new column `zip_category` which will categorize the zip_bins into 4 categories based on what we observed in the exploratory data analysis. The categories are as follows: Unknown, International, High Density Zip, and others. The reason behind creating this this new column is to capture the impact of these specific zips on the response to wave 1."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# convert to categorical\n",
    "intuit['zip_bins']= intuit.zip_bins.astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['version1'] = intuit['version1'].astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['upgraded'] = intuit['upgraded'].astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['bizflag'] = intuit['bizflag'].astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['owntaxprod'] = intuit['owntaxprod'].astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['training'] = intuit['training'].astype('category')\n",
    "intuit['res1_yes'] = intuit['res1_yes'].astype('category')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "intuit['zip_category'] = [\n",
    "    \"Unknown\" if zip5 == \"00000\" else \n",
    "    \"International\" if zip5 == \"99999\" else \n",
    "    \"High_density_zip\" if zip5 in [\"00801\",\"00804\"] else\n",
    "    \"Other\"\n",
    "    for zip5, zip_bin in zip(intuit['zip5'], intuit['zip_bins'])\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert to categorical type\n",
    "intuit['zip_category'] = pd.Categorical(intuit['zip_category'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Split the data into training and test sets\n",
    "train_data = intuit[intuit[\"training\"] == 1]\n",
    "test_data = intuit[intuit[\"training\"] == 0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Building Logistic Models on Wave 1 Training Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

      "Chi-squared: 2289.751, df(29), p.value < 0.001 \n",

      "zip_bins    1.003  0.003\n",
      "sex         1.001  0.001\n",
      "bizflag     1.000  0.000\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "features1 = ['zip_bins', 'sex','bizflag', 'numords', 'dollars', 'last', 'sincepurch', 'version1', 'owntaxprod', 'upgraded']\n",
    "target = 'res1_yes'\n",
    "\n",
    "lr1 = rsm.model.logistic(\n",
    "    data={\"intuit\": train_data},\n",
    "    rvar=target,\n",
    "    lev=1,\n",
    "    evar=features1,\n",
    ")\n",
    "lr1.summary(vif=True)"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 66,

   "outputs": [

     "data": {
      "image/png": "",

      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "lr1.plot(\"vimp\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Running the model using all of features has a Pseudo R-squared of 0.114 and is statistically significant with Chi-squared p-value < .001. The model does not have multicollinearity issues, as all features have VIF < 5.\n",
    "\n",
    "Next we will use `zip_category` as a feature in the model to capture the effect of the highly concentrated zips we explored earlier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Logistic regression (GLM)\n",
      "Data                 : intuit\n",
      "Response variable    : res1_yes\n",
      "Level                : 1\n",
      "Explanatory variables: zip_bins, zip_category, sex, bizflag, numords, dollars, last, version1, owntaxprod, upgraded\n",
      "Null hyp.: There is no effect of x on res1_yes\n",
      "Alt. hyp.: There is an effect of x on res1_yes\n",

    "First we will calculate the break-even response rate and then plot the gains chart and lift chart to evaluate the model's performance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.0235"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 20,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "cost = 1.41\n",
    "margin = 60\n",
    "\n",
    "breakeven_response_rate = cost / margin\n",
    "breakeven_response_rate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The calculated break-even response rate is 0.0235, which will be used as a cut-off to classify the customers as targets for the mailing.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following step we are going to predict the probability of response to wave 1 for using the three logistcs models we built earlier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "intuit['pred_logit_1_wave_1'] = lr1.predict(data=intuit)['prediction']\n",
    "intuit['pred_logit_2_wave_1'] = lr2.predict(data=intuit)['prediction']\n",
    "intuit['pred_logit_3_wave_1'] = lr3.predict(data=intuit)['prediction']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we will compare the predicted probabilities against the cut-off to classify the customers as targets for the mailing."
   ]

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],

    "intuit[\"target_logit_3_wave_1\"] = intuit[\"pred_logit_3_wave_1\"] > breakeven_response_rate"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Looking at the chart, if we have targeted 20% of the customers who are most likely to upgrade based on the model, we can capture 60% of the customers who actually upgraded. If we targeted 50% we would capture 80% of the customers who actually upgraded."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we will calculate the profit and ROME for the three logistic models using the test data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def perf_calc_wave_1(dat=intuit,cost=1,margin=10, target=\"\", perf=\"\", lev=1):\n",
    "    dat = dat[dat.training == 0]\n",
    "    print(f\"sample size = {len(dat)}\")\n",
    "    # targeted\n",
    "    dat = dat[dat[target]==True]\n",
    "    nr_targeted = dat.shape[0]\n",
    "    print(f\"nr_targeted = {nr_targeted}\")\n",
    "    # Response\n",
    "    response_rate = (dat[perf] == lev).mean()\n",
    "    print(f\"response_rate = {response_rate}\")\n",
    "    nr_responses = (dat[perf] == lev).sum()\n",
    "    print(f\"nr_responses = {nr_responses}\")\n",
    "    # Financial\n",
    "    message_cost = cost * nr_targeted\n",
    "    revenue = nr_responses * margin\n",
    "    print(f\"revenue = {revenue}\")\n",
    "    profit = revenue - message_cost\n",
    "    print(f\"profit = {profit}\")\n",
    "    ROME = profit / message_cost\n",
    "    print(f\"ROME = {ROME}\")\n",
    "    return profit, ROME, response_rate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "name": "stdout",

     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "profit_target_logit_1_wave_1, ROME_target_logit_1_wave_1,response_rate_target_logit_1_wave_1 = perf_calc_wave_1(intuit, cost=1.42, margin=60, target=\"target_logit_1_wave_1\", perf=\"res1_yes\", lev=1)\n",
    "profit_target_logit_2_wave_1, ROME_target_logit_2_wave_1,response_rate_target_logit_2_wave_1 = perf_calc_wave_1(intuit, cost=1.42, margin=60, target=\"target_logit_2_wave_1\", perf=\"res1_yes\", lev=1)\n",
    "profit_target_logit_3_wave_1, ROME_target_logit_3_wave_1,response_rate_target_logit_3_wave_1 = perf_calc_wave_1(intuit, cost=1.42, margin=60, target=\"target_logit_3_wave_1\", perf=\"res1_yes\", lev=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# present the results in a table\n",
    "results = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"Model\": [\"Logit 1\", \"Logit 2\", \"Logit 3\"],\n",
    "    \"Profit\": [profit_target_logit_1_wave_1, profit_target_logit_2_wave_1, profit_target_logit_3_wave_1],\n",
    "    \"ROME\": [ROME_target_logit_1_wave_1, ROME_target_logit_2_wave_1, ROME_target_logit_3_wave_1],\n",
    "    \"Response Rate\": [response_rate_target_logit_1_wave_1, response_rate_target_logit_2_wave_1, response_rate_target_logit_3_wave_1]\n",
    "})\n",
    "results"
   ]

       "           Model   Profit      ROME  Response Rate\n",
       "0  Spam Test Set  34455.0  1.086052       0.049022"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 26,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# calculate number of positive responses in the test set\n",
    "nr_responses_test = len(test_data[test_data[\"res1_yes\"] == 1])\n",
    "\n",
    "# count the data set size\n",
    "nr_targeted_test = len(test_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "# calculate the response rate\n",
    "response_rate_test = nr_responses_test / nr_targeted_test\n",
    "\n",
    "# calculate the profit\n",
    "profit_test = nr_responses_test * margin - nr_targeted_test * cost\n",
    "\n",
    "# calculate the ROME\n",
    "ROME_test = profit_test / (nr_targeted_test * cost)\n",
    "\n",
    "# present the results in a table\n",
    "results_test = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"Model\": [\"Spam Test Set\"],\n",
    "    \"Profit\": [profit_test],\n",
    "    \"ROME\": [ROME_test],\n",
    "    \"Response Rate\": [response_rate_test]\n",
    "})\n",
    "results_test"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we have used our logistic model instead of spamming all customers in wave 1, we would have made $28,149 more."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Building Neural Network Models on Wave 1 Training Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before building the neural network model, we will standardize the numerical variables. For the categorical variables, we will use one-hot encoding, which is built in in the pyrsm function, to convert them into numerical variables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],

    "\n",

   ]

    "First we will be creating a train-test split to maintain the same proportions of responses in both the training and testing subsets."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# shuffle split\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit\n",
    "sssplit = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.5, random_state=1234)\n",
    "\n",
    "intuit[\"training\"] = 0\n",
    "for train_index, test_index in sssplit.split(intuit, intuit.res1_yes):\n",
    "    intuit.iloc[train_index, intuit.columns.get_loc(\"training\")] = 1"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we will fine-tune the neural network classifier by optimizing its architecture for predictive performance. We will utilize GridSearchCV to conduct an exhaustive search over a predefined range of hidden layer sizes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn import metrics\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n",
    "# Corrected and expanded list of hidden layer sizes, ensuring all combinations up to (5,5) are included\n",
    "hls = [\n",
    "        (1,), (2,), (3,), (4,), (5,),\n",
    "#        (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (1,5),\n",
    "#        (2,1), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (2,5),\n",
    "#        (3,1), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4), (3,5),\n",
    "#        (4,1), (4,2), (4,3), (4,4), (4,5),\n",
    "#        (5,1), (5,2), (5,3), (5,4), (5,5)\n",
    "       ]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Generate every possible permutation of the given hidden layer sizes up to (5,5)\n",
    "# Since the task does not specify the length of permutations, assume single combinations are sufficient\n",
    "# Therefore, permutations in this context might not be the right operation since we're dealing with unique combinations\n",
    "# Instead, we ensure all combinations up to (5,5) are included in hls, as above\n",
    "\n",
    "# Deduplicate hls to ensure all entries are unique\n",
    "unique_hls = list(set(hls))  # Convert to set and back to list to remove duplicates\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sort the list for better readability\n",
    "unique_hls.sort()\n",
    "\n",
    "unique_hls\n",
    "\n",
    "param_grid = {\"hidden_layer_sizes\": hls}\n",
    "scoring = {\"AUC\": \"roc_auc\"} # we should add more metrics here\n",
    "\n",
    "clf_cv = GridSearchCV(\n",
    "    clf1.fitted, param_grid, scoring=scoring, cv=5, n_jobs=4, refit=\"AUC\", verbose=5 # f different chu\n",
    "    \n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After running the grid search, the optimal architecture was determined to be a single hidden layer with 2 nodes. This architecture achieved the highest AUC score of 0.769, which is consistent with the performance of the second model we built earlier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Wave 2 Projection"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Given that both, the logistic and neural network models, have similar performance, we will use the logistic model to predict the response to wave 2. This is because the logistic model is easier to interpret and explain to stakeholders. In addition, the logistic model is less computationally expensive and requires less data to train, which makes it more practical for real-time predictions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Fisrt we will predict the probability of response to wave 2 using the third logistic model divided by two as given in the instructions. Then we will decide who to target for wave 2 based on the cut-off we calculated earlier. Using this list of targeted customers, we will calculate the response rate and project it to the entire population to calculate the expected profit and ROME."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "intuit['pred_best_wave_2'] = intuit['pred_logit_3_wave_1']/2\n",
    "intuit[\"target_for_wave2\"] = intuit[\"pred_best_wave_2\"] > breakeven_response_rate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "test_response_rate_actual = 0.04802666666666667\n",
      "perc_targeted_using_best_model = 0.2489\n",
      "test_targeted_response_rate = 0.1163\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Calculate the actual response rate for the test group where \"training\" is 0 and \"res1_yes\" is 1\n",
    "test_response_rate_actual = len(intuit[(intuit[\"training\"] == 0) & (intuit[\"res1_yes\"] == 1)]) / len(intuit[intuit[\"training\"] == 0])\n",
    "print(f\"test_response_rate_actual = {test_response_rate_actual}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate the percentage of users targeted using the best model among those who were in the test group, did not respond to the first wave, and were decided to be targeted in the second wave.\n",
    "perc_targeted_using_best_model = len(intuit[(intuit['training'] == 0) & (intuit['res1_yes'] == 0) & (intuit['target_for_wave2'] == True)]) / len(intuit[(intuit['training'] == 0) & (intuit['res1_yes'] == 0)])\n",
    "print(f\"perc_targeted_using_best_model = {perc_targeted_using_best_model:.4f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate the targeted response rate in the test group using the best model. This is the proportion of users who were targeted in the second wave and responded positively.\n",
    "test_targeted_response_rate = len(intuit[(intuit['training'] == 0) & (intuit['target_for_wave2'] == True) & (intuit['res1_yes'] == 1)]) / len(intuit[(intuit['training'] == 0) & (intuit['target_for_wave2'] == True)])\n",
    "print(f\"test_targeted_response_rate = {test_targeted_response_rate:.4f}\")"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "full_customer = 801821\n",
    "print(f\"sample size = {full_customer}\")\n",
    "customers_remaining_after_wave_1 = 801821 - 38487 # from Question\n",
    "print(f\"customers_remaining_after_wave_1 = {customers_remaining_after_wave_1}\")\n",
    "# targeted\n",
    "nr_targeted = customers_remaining_after_wave_1 * perc_targeted_using_best_model\n",
    "print(f\"nr_targeted = {nr_targeted}\")\n",
    "# Response\n",
    "test_targeted_response_rate\n",
    "print(f\"response_rate = {test_targeted_response_rate}\")\n",
    "nr_responses = nr_targeted * test_targeted_response_rate\n",
    "print(f\"nr_responses = {nr_responses}\")\n",
    "# Financial\n",
    "message_cost = cost * nr_targeted\n",
    "print(f\"message_cost = {message_cost}\")\n",
    "revenue = nr_responses * margin\n",
    "print(f\"revenue = {revenue}\")\n",
    "profit = revenue - message_cost\n",
    "print(f\"profit = {profit}\")\n",
    "ROME = profit / message_cost\n",
    "print(f\"ROME = {ROME}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# present the results in a table\n",
    "results_wave_2_method1 = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    \"Model\": [\"Logit Method 1\"],\n",
    "    \"Profit\": [profit],\n",
    "    \"ROME\": [ROME],\n",
    "    \"Response Rate\": [test_targeted_response_rate]\n",
    "})\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Comparing the outcomes of two different marketing campaign strategiestargeted marketing using the 'Logit 3' model and a 'Spam All' approachseveral key performance metrics stand out:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Sample Size**: Both campaigns began with the same sample size of 801,821 and a similar number of customers remaining after wave 1 (763,334).\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Number Targeted**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Targeted a specific subset of 190,004.93 customers.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Targeted all remaining customers (763,334).\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Response Rate**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Achieved a higher response rate of 7.271%.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Achieved a lower response rate of 2.401%.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Number of Responses**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Garnered 13,816.15 positive responses.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Garnered more absolute responses at 18,330.19 due to the larger number targeted.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Message Cost**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Incurred a lower cost at 267,906.95.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Incurred a significantly higher cost at 1,076,300.94.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. **Revenue**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Generated a higher revenue of 828,968.87.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Generated a lower revenue of 1,099,811.63 (despite the higher number of responses, indicating possibly lower revenue per response).\n",
    "\n",
    "7. **Profit**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Yielded a substantial profit of 561,061.92.\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Yielded a much smaller profit of 23,510.69.\n",
    "\n",
    "8. **Return on Marketing Expenditure (ROME)**:\n",
    "   - **Logit 3**: Delivered a far greater ROME of 2.094 (a 209% return on the marketing investment).\n",
    "   - **Spam All**: Delivered a ROME of just 0.0218 (a 2.18% return), which is significantly lower than the targeted approach.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Conclusion:\n",
    "The 'Logit 3' targeted campaign strategy is far superior to the 'Spam All' approach across all measured metrics, particularly in terms of efficiency (ROME) and effectiveness (profit and response rate). It highlights the importance of targeted marketing in not only generating more favorable response rates but also in ensuring cost-effective campaigns that maximize profit and return on investment. The 'Spam All' strategy, while generating a larger number of responses, is less efficient, resulting in substantially lower profit and ROME. This comparison underscores the value of using predictive modeling to inform marketing strategies."
   ]

    "# Overwrite the specified columns with values from the Parquet file\n",
    "intuit[['numords', 'dollars', 'last', 'sincepurch']] = pd.read_parquet(\"data/intuit75k.parquet\")[['numords', 'dollars', 'last', 'sincepurch']]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Filter the dataset to include only rows where training = 0 (test set)\n",
    "test_set = intuit[intuit['training'] == 0]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Separate the dataset into two groups based on 'mailto_wave2'\n",
    "targeted_for_upgrade = test_set[test_set['mailto_wave2'] == True]\n",
    "not_targeted_for_upgrade = test_set[test_set['mailto_wave2'] == False]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compare the characteristics of the two groups\n",
    "comparison_columns = ['numords', 'dollars', 'last', 'sincepurch']\n",
    "comparison_summary = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'Metric': comparison_columns,\n",
    "    'Targeted_Mean': [targeted_for_upgrade[col].mean() for col in comparison_columns],\n",
    "    'Not_Targeted_Mean': [not_targeted_for_upgrade[col].mean() for col in comparison_columns],\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "comparison_summary"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [

    "# Data preparation for plotting\n",
    "metrics = comparison_summary['Metric']\n",
    "targeted_means = comparison_summary['Targeted_Mean']\n",
    "not_targeted_means = comparison_summary['Not_Targeted_Mean']\n",
    "\n",
    "x = range(len(metrics))  # the label locations\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "rects1 = ax.bar(x, targeted_means, 0.4, label='Targeted for Upgrade')\n",
    "rects2 = ax.bar([p + 0.4 for p in x], not_targeted_means, 0.4, label='Not Targeted for Upgrade')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Means')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Comparison of Business Characteristics by Wave 2 Targeting')\n",
    "ax.set_xticks([p + 0.2 for p in x])\n",
    "ax.set_xticklabels(metrics)\n",
    "ax.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Autolabel function to display the height of bars\n",
    "def autolabel(rects):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height.\"\"\"\n",
    "    for rect in rects:\n",
    "        height = rect.get_height()\n",
    "        ax.annotate('{}'.format(round(height, 2)),\n",
    "                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),\n",
    "                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset\n",
    "                    textcoords=\"offset points\",\n",
    "                    ha='center', va='bottom')\n",
    "\n",
    "autolabel(rects1)\n",
    "autolabel(rects2)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.tight_layout()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the charts and calculated means above we can see the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Businesses Targeted for Upgrades** exhibit distinct characteristics compared to those not targeted, highlighting patterns of higher engagement, spending, and loyalty.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Key Findings**:\n",
    "  - **Number of Orders (`numords`)**: Targeted businesses have an average of 2.792 orders, significantly higher than the 1.858 average orders of non-targeted businesses. This suggests targeted businesses engage more frequently with the company.\n",
    "  - **Dollar Amount Spent (`dollars`)**: On average, targeted businesses spend $128.94, substantially more than the $81.92 average spend of non-targeted businesses, indicating higher monetary value from these customers.\n",
    "  - **Last Purchase (`last`)**: The average time since the last purchase for targeted businesses is 9.92 days, compared to 17.65 days for non-targeted businesses. This shows targeted businesses have more recent interactions.\n",
    "  - **Time Since First Purchase (`sincepurch`)**: Targeted businesses have been customers for an average of 22.62 days, longer than the 13.40 days for non-targeted businesses, demonstrating a longer-term relationship with the company."
